Apprentissage Statistique

Bank marketing

03 septembre, 2020

Abstract:

The data is related with direct marketing campaigns (based on phone calls) of a Portuguese banking institution. The aim of this project is to predict if a client will subscribe a term deposit (variable y). The dataset is constructed from 41188 observations which correspond to real customers recording. There are 21 variables which includes information about the client, the campaign and the economic context. The variable y is the target variable which indicates whether the customer has subscribed a term deposit or not. It appears that only a small proportion of our sample has subscribed a term deposit (11%, so the classes are not equally represented). Thus we are facing an issue of imbalanced data.

1.1 Features

Related to the client:

  • Age
  • Job: admin., blue-collar, entrepreneur, housemaid, management, retired, self-employed, services, student, technician, unemployed, unknown
  • Marital: divorced, married, single, unknown
  • Education: basic.4y, basic.6y, basic.9y, high.school, illiterate, professional.course, university.degree, unknown
  • Default: has credit in default?
  • Housing: has housing loan?
  • Loan: has personal loan?

Related with the last contact of the current campaign:

  • Contact: contact communication type
  • Month: last contact month of year
  • Day_of_week: last contact day of the week
  • Duration: last contact duration in seconds

Important note: this attribute highly affects the output target (e.g., if duration=0 then y=no). Yet, the duration is not known before a call is performed. Also, after the end of the call y is obviously known. Thus, this input should only be included for benchmark purposes and should be discarded if the intention is to have a realistic predictive model.

Other attributes:

  • Campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign for this client
  • Pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (999 means client was not previously contacted)
  • Previous: number of contacts performed before this campaign
  • Poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign (failure,nonexistent,success)

Social and economic context attributes:

  • Emp.var.rate: employment variation rate - quarterly indicator
  • Cons.price.idx: consumer price index - monthly indicator
  • Cons.conf.idx: consumer confidence index - monthly indicator
  • Euribor3m: euribor 3 month rate - daily indicator
  • Nr.employed: number of employees - quarterly indicator

Finally our targeted variable:

  • y: has the client subscribed a term deposit?

1.2 Imbalanced data

Regarding our output, the first thing we can observe is that we face an unbalanced two-levels categorical variable - that is, we have one class which outnumbers the other by a large proportion in the response variable:

There is indeed 88.7% of no against only 11.3% of yes. This issue is common in binary classification problems, and do not consider this issue in the ML model could lead to a situation of Accuracy paradox: excellent accuracy (such as 90% of observations correctly classified), but which only reflecting the underlying class distribution. Hence, it is important to learn how to deal with such problems, and as you will see there are mainly two approaches to treat imbalanced data: Cost Sensitive Learning and resampling methods.

1.2.1 Cost Sensitive Learning

It is imperative to choose the evaluation metric of your model correctly. Indeed when dealing with imbalanced data, the accuracy (percentage of observations correctly classified) is no longer the indicator of interest: we will focus on other parameters. But first lets define four fundamental terms:

  • True Positives (TP): instance that is positive and is classified correctly as positive
  • True Negatives (TN): instance that is negative and is classified correctly as negative
  • False Positives (FP): instance that is negative but is classified wrongly as positive
  • False Negatives (FN): instance that is positive but is classified incorrectly as negative

Depending on your work you may be interested by studying one or several of these category. A good model should have a high rate of correctly classified instances (TP & TN) and a low rate of incorrectly classified one (FP & FN). Thus when constructing the confusion matrix, alternative parameters such as Precision, Sensitivity and Specificity are useful.

Recall:

Precision is the number of positive predictions divided by the total number of positive class values predicted: TP / (TP+FP). A low precision can thus indicate a large number of False Positives.

Sensitivity is the number of positive predictions divided by the number of positive class values : TP / (TP+FN). A low sensitivity can thus indicate a large number of False Negatives.

Specificity is the number of negative predictions divided by the number of negative class values : TN / (TN+FP).

There are also some other metrics that can be useful to see which model is the most efficient:

  • kappa: give classification accuracy normalized by the imbalance of the classes in the data

  • the ROC curve: show the performance of a classification model at all classification thresholds. It is one of the most used performance metrics. The curve is formed by plotting the sensitivity (benefits) and the specificity (costs). Thus, the larger the area under ROC curve, higher will be the accuracy.

  • F1 score : \(F1 = 2 \times \frac{precision \times sensitivity}{precision + sensitivity}\)

The coefficient ranges from 0 to 1, where 1 means perfect precision & sensitivity.

1.2.2 Undersampling

This approach is part of the resampling methods, that involves modifying the initial dataset to create balanced data distribution. The undersampling consists to resample the dataset by deleting instances from the over-represented class. However, since this method involves removing observations, it is best to use with large dataset to limit information loss. There are two ways for deleting observations:

  • by random undersampling: observations from majority class which are randomly eliminated until the data set gets balanced

  • by informative undersampling: the deleted observations follows a pre-specified selection criterion

1.2.3 Oversampling

As you may have guessed, this method involves doing the reverse of the undersampling method. Hence it works with the minority class, and replicates the observations to balance the data. In the same way, oversampling can be done randomly or informatively.

However since it consists of simply adds replicated observations from the original dataset, it can increase the likelihood of overfitting.

1.2.4 Synthetic Data Generation

Instead of simply replicating and adding the observations from the minority class, the aim of this method is to balance class distribution by generating synthetic samples by using systematic algorithms such as SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique).

Unlike the previous oversampling method, the SMOTE algorithm generates artificial data based on feature space similarities from minority samples, and uses bootstrapping and k-nn.The minority class is thus over-sampled by introducing synthetic examples along the line segments joining any/all of the k minority class nearest neighbors. Depending upon the amount of over-sampling required, neighbors from the k nearest neighbors are randomly chosen.

We would therefore see some of these methods when we will create our training set. But first lets prepare our data.

  1. Housing & loan

As we said before, there is the same number of NAs for these two variables and it is also the same individuals. This let us think that there is a possible correlation link between the two variables that can cause multicolinearity issue.

library(stats)
chisq.test(bank$loan, bank$housing)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  bank$loan and bank$housing
## X-squared = 84.622, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16

The associated p-value is lower than a 0.001 threshold: for a confidence level of 99% we can not reject that there is no association between the to features. Thus, we must remove one of them, so lets see the relation with the output y.

chisq.test(bank$housing, bank$y)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  bank$housing and bank$y
## X-squared = 5.2924, df = 1, p-value = 0.02142
chisq.test(bank$loan, bank$y)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  bank$loan and bank$y
## X-squared = 0.68594, df = 1, p-value = 0.4075

Regarding those test, we can see that the p-value associated to the Chi-squared test between loan and y equals to 0.4075, which is higher than a 0.01-threshold whereas the p-value associated to the Chi-squared test between housing and y equals to 0.021 which is lower 0.05. So, for a confidence level of 99%, theres no association between y and loan. We thus remove this feature from the dataset:

bank <- bank[,!(names(bank) %in% c("loan"))]

Now there still are 984 missing values for housing that we could replace by the median grouped by job, marital status and level of education. But for this exercise we will simply remove the missing values.

1.4.2 Bivariate analysis

1.4.2.1 Correlation between numerical features

For now we do not explore the distribution of our set of numeric features. Indeed we have just briefly explored these social and economic context attributes at the beginning by looking at their summary statistic, and we saw that is was not useful to study them in detail since they only give an evolution of external factors. However what we can study here is weather their evolution are correlated or not, an issue that we want to avoid. So lets figure out this point:

# Correlation for numeric variables (except "campaign")
num_data <- select_if(bank[,-c(9)],is.numeric)

num_cor <- cor(num_data, method = "pearson") 

# Correlogramme 
corrplot(num_cor, method ="color", type="upper", order = "hclust", 
         tl.col="black", addCoef.col = "black", number.cex = .7, tl.srt=45, 
         tl.cex = 0.8, diag = FALSE)

We can observe that three pairs of features (nr.employed & emp.var.rate; nr.employed & euribor3m; emp.var.rate & euribor3m) present a high positive correlation (>0.9). As we know it can cause multicolinearity issue, and we thus have to remove some of these variables.

But first lets make a little reminder regarding our variable euribor3m: the 3-month Euribor interest rate is the interest rate at which a selection of European banks lend each other funds (in euro), and whose loans have a maturity of 3 months. One can then ask ourselves what kind of correlation there could be with the evolution of the number of employees within the bank (nr.employed & emp.var.rate). Indeed the link does not seem obvious, and one could therefore make the hypothesis of a spurious correlation (e.g.there is no causal effect) between euribor3m and emp.var.rate / nr.employed.

However the relation between the employment variation rate (emp.var.rate) and the number of employees (nr.employed) appears obvious. So lets see how these two features are correlated with our target variable.

Since y is a categorical variable with two levels (also called a dichotomous variable), with can use a point-biserial correlation (1) to estimate the relation, which is equivalent to the Pearson correlation (2). We will show you the two method:

# === (1) Compute the point-biserial correlation ===
library(ltm)
biserial.cor(bank$emp.var.rate, bank$y, use = c("all.obs", "complete.obs"), level = 1)
## [1] 0.2962391
biserial.cor(bank$nr.employed, bank$y, use = c("all.obs", "complete.obs"), level = 1)
## [1] 0.3528059
# === (2) Create new data partition ===
interest_feature <- c("y", "nr.employed", "emp.var.rate")
mydata <- bank[,interest_feature]
mydata <- mydata %>% mutate(y = if_else(y == "yes", "1", "0")) 
mydata$y <- as.numeric(mydata$y)

# Compute the Pearson correlation 
biserial_cor <- cor(mydata, method = "pearson") 

# Correlogramme 
corrplot(biserial_cor, method ="color", type="upper", order = "hclust", 
         tl.col="black", addCoef.col = "black", number.cex = .7, tl.srt=45, 
         tl.cex = 0.8, diag = FALSE)

# The variable "nr.employed" is the one with the higher correlation with y. 
# We will therefore keep this one and remove the other.

bank <- bank[,!(names(bank) %in% c("emp.var.rate"))]

1.4.2.2 Correlation between character features

In the same way we can have a look on the correlation with our other set of variables, and see if they show a dependency on each other. We will use Cramers V to study the different links. The Cramers V is computed as follow:

\[ V = \sqrt{\frac{\chi^2}{n . \left( min\left(r, c \right) -1\right)}} \]

With: - \(n\) the size of the sample - \(r\) the number of rows in our contingency table - \(c\) the number of columns in our contingency table

# Data partition 
chr_data <- select_if(bank[, -c(17)], ~is.character(.))

# Create contingency tables
cont_table <- matrix(NA, ncol(chr_data), ncol(chr_data))

for (i in (1:ncol(chr_data))){
  for (j in (1:ncol(chr_data))){
    x <- table(chr_data[, i], chr_data[, j])
    # Compute chi-square results
    chisq_results = chisq.test(x)
    # We compute the coefficients and keep only 3 digits
    cont_table[i, j] = round(sqrt(chisq_results$statistic/(nrow(chr_data) * 
                                                          (min(dim(x)) -1))), 3)
  }
}

# We rename the rows and columns in the same way as a correlation matrix 
rownames(cont_table) <- colnames(chr_data)
colnames(cont_table) <- colnames(chr_data)


# Correlogramme 
corrplot(cont_table, method ="color", type="upper", 
         tl.col="black", addCoef.col = "black", number.cex = .75, tl.srt=45, 
         tl.cex = 0.8, diag = FALSE)

The correlation matrix does not show any important correlation between features (except for pdays & poutcome). So one more time lets see which of these two is the less correlated with our target variable:

# We create contingency tables 
mytable1 <- table(bank$pdays, bank$y)
mytable2 <- table(bank$poutcome, bank$y)

library(rcompanion)
cramerV(mytable1)
## Cramer V 
##   0.3255
cramerV(mytable2)
## Cramer V 
##   0.3209

It seems like pdays and poutcome are both correlated to y with a Cramers coefficient around 0.32. But pdays seems to have a bit higher coefficient o we will keep only this one for the next step of the study.

2.1.3 Setting up the validation methods

# function to set up random seeds
setSeeds <- function(method = "cv", numbers = 1, repeats = 1, tunes = NULL, seed = 1237) {
  #B is the number of resamples and integer vector of M (numbers + tune length if any)
  B <- if (method == "cv") numbers
  else if(method == "repeatedcv") numbers * repeats
  else NULL
  
  if(is.null(length)) {
    seeds <- NULL
  } else {
    set.seed(seed = seed)
    seeds <- vector(mode = "list", length = B)
    seeds <- lapply(seeds, function(x) sample.int(n = 1000000, size = numbers + ifelse(is.null(tunes), 0, tunes)))
    seeds[[length(seeds) + 1]] <- sample.int(n = 1000000, size = 1)
  }
  # return seeds
  seeds
}


# Seeds
rcvSeeds <- setSeeds(method = "repeatedcv", 
                      numbers = 5, repeats = 5, 
                      tunes = 100, seed = 777)

# Configure the trainControl argument for cross-validation
K5_CV <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5, 
                      classProbs = TRUE, 
                      savePredictions = TRUE, 
                      seeds = rcvSeeds,
                      summaryFunction = twoClassSummary,
                      allowParallel = TRUE)

On the training set, the accuracy is 89.8%. However as explained with imbalanced dataset, the Sensitivity rate is not so high: only 23.4%%. This means that the model manages to classify the observations correctly 9 times out of 10, but only one fifth of the interested customers, which are our concern, are correctly detected. These results reflect typically the situation of accuracy paradox in which the accuracy measures tell the story that we have excellent accuracy (such as 90%), but it is only reflecting the underlying class distribution. Since accuracy with imbalanced data is misleading, we can regard other parameters such as the kappa (0.3) which give classification accuracy normalized by the imbalance of the classes.

2.5 Weighted Decision tree

An alternative to resampling the data is to make the classifier aware of the imbalanced data by incorporating the weights of the classes into a cost function. This methods aims therefore to assign the minority class with a higher weight, and the majority class with a lower weight.

set.seed(777)

K5_CV <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5, classProbs = TRUE, 
                           savePredictions = TRUE, seeds = rcvSeeds,
                           allowParallel = TRUE, summaryFunction =  twoClassSummary)

# class weights 
k <- .5
classWeights <- ifelse(bank_train$resp == "yes",
                       (1/table(bank_train$resp)[1]) * k,
                       (1/table(bank_train$resp)[2]) * (1-k))


# Parameter tuning
#grid <- expand.grid(cp = seq(from = 0.001, to = 0.005, by = 0.001))
grid <- expand.grid(cp = .02)

# Model
WDTree <- train(resp ~ ., 
               data = bank_train, 
               method = "rpart",
               tuneGrid = grid,
               trControl = K5_CV,
               weights = classWeights)

# Model performances
WDTree_pred <- predict(WDTree, newdata = bank_test)

confus_WDTree <- confusionMatrix(data = WDTree_pred, reference = bank_test$resp,
                       positive="yes", mode = "everything")

By looking at this graph, we can see that the best ROC is obtained with a maximum tree depth of 6, a number of boosting iterations of 250 and a low learning rate (eta) of 0.02. However the blue curve doesnt have a good shape: it falls downs when the number of boosting iterations increase, but also when the learning rate becomes greater. Indeed, a high value of Max Tree Depth can make the model to complex and more likely to overfit. Thats why in order to have a better model, one would prefer a more stable model - that is a model with the following tuning parameter :

  • eta = 0.1
  • nrounds = 450
  • max_depth = 2

2.8 SVM

The Support Vector Machine (SVM) is a useful classification technique. As you know in real life data the separation boundary is generally non-linear, and the SVM algorithm allows to perform a non-linear classification using what is called the kernel trick. There are several kernel transformations, but the two most commonly used are the polynomial and radial kernel.

3 Model comparison

We tried a lot of different model to predict if a client will subscribe a term deposit. Although they perform in a different way, each of these models seem to present different but quite similar results on unseen data. So lets evaluate them by looking at the different metrics they present, like sensitivity, ROC, F1 score or Gini coefficient, such metrics that perform better in evaluating model performance for imbalanced datasets.

3.1 Sensitivity

models <- list(Logit = logit3,
               LDA = lda,
               DecisionTree = DTree,
               WeightedDecisionTree = WDTree,
               RandomForest = rf,
               XGBoost = xgb,
               SVM = svm)

res <- resamples(models)

models_list <- c("Logit",
                 "LDA",
                 "DecisionTree",
                 "WeightedDecisionTree",
                 "RandomForest",
                 "XGBoost",
                 "SVM")

df = data.frame()
for (i in models_list){
  x = data.frame (model = i, 
                  Sens = res$values[paste(i,"Sens", sep = "~")],
                  ROC = res$values[paste(i,"ROC", sep = "~")])
  x <- x %>% rename(Sens = paste(i,"Sens", sep = "."))
  x <- x %>% rename(ROC = paste(i,"ROC", sep = "."))
  df <- rbind(df,x)
}

# Sensitivity
ggplot(data = df, aes(x = fct_reorder(model, Sens, .desc = T), 
                      y = Sens, fill = model)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.colour = "darkblue", outlier.size = 2, alpha=0.2) +
  theme_model + 
  labs(x = "", y = "Sensitivity") +
  ggtitle("Model performance by Sensitivity")

When comparing the different model by having a look on the sensitivity comparison, we can see that the model based on WeightedDecisionTree is from far the one that show the best prediction. At the opposite, the gradient boosting approach represented by XGBoost seems to perform poorly when predicting the targeted client.

3.2 F1 score

As explained at the beginning, this metrics can be considered as the harmonic mean of the precision and the sensitivity. The closer it is to 1, the better the precision & sensitivity.

# Extract the F1 score from the confusion matrix
F1 <- c(confus_logit$byClass[7],
        confus_lda$byClass[7],
        confus_DTree$byClass[7],
        confus_WDTree$byClass[7],
        confus_rf$byClass[7],
        confus_xgb$byClass[7],
        confus_svm$byClass[7])
                    
F1_table <- data.frame(model = models_list, 
           F1_score = F1)

# Keep only 3 digits
F1_table$F1_score <- round(F1_table$F1_score,3)


ggplot(data = F1_table, 
       aes(x = fct_reorder(model, F1_score, .desc = T),
           y = F1_score,
           fill = model)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", alpha=0.5) + 
  labs(x = "", y = "F1 score") +
  geom_text(aes(label = F1_score, vjust = -0.3)) +
  theme_model +
  ggtitle("Model performance by F1 score") +
  coord_cartesian(ylim=c(.4, .5))

If the WeightedDecisionTree presents the best sensitivity, it is also because this model predict much more positive values (client with resp = yes). Thus the precision of this model is among the worst of the tested model (0.36), which lead to a poor F1 score, whose highest value is obtained with the RandomForest model (0.497).

However if we look at both sensitivity & F1 score performances, we can see that the SVM model is the more accurate.

3.3 ROC & Gini coefficient

If the two first metrics weve just studied focused only on the positive prediction, the ROC allows to visualize the trade-off between the true positive rate and the false positive rate.

But before plotting the ROC, we can have a look on the Gini coefficient which is a popular metric for imbalanced class values. It is calculated as follows : \((2 \times AUC) - 1\).

This coefficient represents how close is a model to being a perfect classifier (represented by a Gini coefficient of 1). At the opposite, a random classifier would get a Gini coefficient of 0.

# Compute Gini coefficient
df$Gini <- (2*df$ROC) - 1

# Gini value
ggplot(data = df, aes(x = fct_reorder(model, Gini, .desc = T), 
                      y = Gini, fill = model)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.colour = "darkblue", outlier.size = 2, alpha=0.2) +
  theme_model + 
  labs(x = "", y = "Gini value") +
  ggtitle("Model performance by Gini")

For the first time, it is the Boosting based method which best perform. The value can be interpreted as the probability that a random positive observation will have a higher estimated probability than a random negative observation: it tells how much a model is able to distinguishing between classes.

So lets plot the curves to see their shape:

A perfect classifier have its ROC curve that form a right angle - that is the curve go along the Y-axis and then along the X-axis.

library(MLeval)

# For the sake of visibility, we only present 3 models
roc <- evalm(list(svm, WDTree, xgb), gnames=c('SVM',
                                              'WeightedDecisionTree',
                                              'XGBoost'),
             silent=TRUE, positive = "yes", plots="r")

Regarding the Gini coefficient, it could be interpreted as the ratio between the area within the ROC curve and the random model line (represented by the diagonal line), and the area between the perfect classifier curve and the random model line.

3.4 Balanced Accuracy

A latest metric and maybe the more evident is the balanced accuracy, which is computed as the average of the correct predictions of each class individually: \((Sensitivity + Specificity) / 2\).

# Extract the Balanced Accuracy from the confusion matrix
Balanced_Acc <- c(confus_logit$byClass[11],
        confus_lda$byClass[11],
        confus_DTree$byClass[11],
        confus_WDTree$byClass[11],
        confus_rf$byClass[11],
        confus_xgb$byClass[11],
        confus_svm$byClass[11])
                    
BalancedAcc_table <- data.frame(model = models_list, 
           Balanced_Accuracy = Balanced_Acc)

# Keep only 3 digits
BalancedAcc_table$Balanced_Accuracy <- round(BalancedAcc_table$Balanced_Accuracy,3)


ggplot(data = BalancedAcc_table, 
       aes(x = fct_reorder(model, Balanced_Accuracy, .desc = T),
           y = Balanced_Accuracy,
           fill = model)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", alpha=0.5) + 
  labs(x = "", y = "Balanced Accuracy") +
  geom_text(aes(label = Balanced_Accuracy, vjust = -0.3)) +
  theme_model +
  ggtitle("Model performance by Balanced Accuracy") +
  coord_cartesian(ylim=c(.7, .75))

Except XGBoost, all the model are pretty close from each other, but the SVM one with radial kernel has the best balanced accuracy (0.74), and is therefore the model that give the best prediction in a general way.

Finally by looking at every metrics, we can also highlight the good performances obtained by the Logistic approach & the Linear Discriminant Analysis.
